awd_titl_txt: I-Corps Sites - Type I: Harvesting an Innovation Ecosystem at a Diverse Regional Comprehensive University for Business Incubation
awd_abstract_narration:
This project proposes to create an I-Corps Site at California State University - Northridge. NSF Innovation Corps (I-Corps) Sites are NSF-funded entities established at universities whose purpose is to nurture and support multiple, local teams to transition their technology concepts into the marketplace. Sites provide infrastructure, advice, resources, networking opportunities, training and modest funding to enable groups to transition their work into the marketplace or into becoming I-Corps Team applicants. I-Corps Sites also strengthen innovation locally and regionally and contribute to the National Innovation Network of mentors, researchers, entrepreneurs and investors

The California State University Northridge (CSUN) I-Corps Site brings together an experienced innovation ecosystem to help foster the growth of potential entrepreneurs on campus and in the San Fernando Valley (SFV) region. The CSUNInnovates! program, a campus-wide program designed to integrate all innovation resources on campus, developed a strategic partnership with the widely known Los Angeles Cleantech Incubator (LACI) to expand on the entrepreneurial support provided to students, faculty, and alumni. LACI@CSUN was created in 2014 out of a vision to create a world-class entrepreneurial capability and culture at CSUN and establish the SFV region's reputation as a leader in technological innovation and entrepreneurship. If successful, this project has the potential to impact both the institution and the region.
org_dir_long_name: Directorate for Technology, Innovation, and Partnerships

por.por_cntn:
The funding of the NSF I-Corps training has been transformative for the CSUN community.  The benefits of this methodology were quickly recognized by the students and faculty and embraced as a platform to quickly articulate and test hypotheses related to unmet market needs.  Teams were allowed to participate in multiple cohorts.  We observed that more successful teams (as measured by interviews, MVP development, etc.) participated in multiple cohorts, even after graduation.

Covid, obviously, hampered our ability to fund travel.  However, the supplemental awards were significant in training students to conduct interviews over Zoom to emulate face-to-face interviews.  Student travel to conferences and customers across the US to conduct customer interviews greatly contributed to the students understanding of of their market unmet needs, and formulated an improved understanding of the performance specifications their solution would need to deliver. 

Finally, we demonstrated that there is an substantial desire for these co-curricular programs among women and people of color as long as they are developed with sensitivity to the constraints faced by these segments.  Several concepts contributed to this: (1) spanish language and female-focused recruitment outreach communicated that CSUN is committed to DEI, (2) shorter, more frequent Zoom training enabled people to participate over lunch (3) Zoom recordings enabled people to "catch-up" if they missed a session. 

I-Corps methodology has become foundational to the CSUN entrepreneur community and has been a key component of the incubator, accelerator, pitch competitions and academic classes.
